data.title: VICI Properties nudges up 2025 AFFO guidance after slight Q3 beat
data.description:
VICI Properties (VICI) posted slightly better-than-expected Q3 earnings on Thursday as revenue grew 4.4% Y/Y and earnings benefited from lower allowance for credit losses.

The REIT that invests in casino and entertainment properties now expects full-year adjusted FFO per share of $2.36-$2.37, vs. the Visible Alpha consensus of $2.37 and its previous guidance of $2.35-$2.37.

Q3 adjusted FFO per share of $0.60, topping the $0.59 Visible Alpha consensus, was flat with $0.60 in Q2 and $0.57 in last year’s Q3.

Total revenue of $1.01B, beating the $1.00B consensus, increased from $1.00B in the prior quarter and $964.7M in the year-ago period.

Income from lease financing receivables, loans, and securities rose to $448.0M from $440.3M in Q2 and $419.1M in Q3 2024.

"In the third quarter of 2025, the compounding nature of our business continued to demonstrate its merit with 4.4% year-over-year revenue growth and 5.3% year-over-year growth in AFFO per share, supporting our 8th consecutive annual dividend increase of $0.0175 per share, representing a 4.0% year-over-year increase," said CEO Edward Pitoniak.

Vici Properties (VICI) stock rose 0.4%  in after-hours trading.

Total operating expenses of $23.4M compared with a benefit of $93.1M in the prior quarter due to a $142M change in its allowance for credit losses, and expenses of $13.1M in the year-ago quarter. The current quarter included a $20.2M benefit from a change in allowance for credit losses.

Adjusted EBITDA of $825.6M climbed from $822.2M in Q2 and $778.0M in last year’s Q3.

Conference call on Oct. 31 at 10:00 AM ET.

data.title: Earnings Snapshot: Apple exceeds consensus with earnings and revenue
Omega Healthcare raises 2025 guidance as favorable backdrop drives Q3 earnings beat
data.description:
Omega Healthcare Investors (OHI) increased its full-year guidance after Q3 earnings topped the consensus estimate, supported by improving occupancy and coverage, the company said on Thursday.

The healthcare REIT now expects 2025 adjusted FFO per share of $3.08-$3.10, vs. the consensus estimate of $3.00, and up from its prior guidance of $3.04-$3.07.

"The backdrop continues to be favorable," said CEO Taylor Pickett. "Operating metrics remain strong, with both occupancy and coverage further improving in the quarter. The pipeline is very active, and we have a strong balance sheet and cost of capital that should allow us to continue to accretively invest."

Q3 adjusted FFO per share $0.79, exceeding the average analyst estimate of $0.76, rose from $0.77 in Q2 and $0.74 in last year’s Q3.

Q3 revenue of $311.6M, topping the consensus estimate of $261.6M, increased from $282.5M in the previous quarter and $276.0M a year ago.

Real estate loans interest income climbed/dropped to $34.4M from $33.0M in Q2 and $33.6M in last year’s Q3.

Expenses fell to $165.3M from $171.9M in the previous quarter and increased from $163.3M a year ago.

Omega Healthcare (OHI) stock rose 0.8% in after-hours trading.

Omega (OHI) completed $150.8M in new investments during the quarter, consisting of real estate acquisitions of $67.3M, real estate loans of $7.92M, and other investments of $75.6M. It completed $978M in new investments in year-to-date.

The REIT said Genesis Healthcare, which filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in July, has made all required contractual rent and interest payments. In Q3 2025, Omega (OHI) recorded rental income of $12.9M, for contractual rent payments received from Genesis, and interest income of $4.3M, consisting of $0.1M of cash interest related to adequate protection payments received and $4.2M of paid-in-kind interest. In October 2025, Genesis paid its full contractual rent and interest of $4.4M.

Conference call on Oct. 31 at 10:00 AM ET.
